Moreover, on his Honour's findings of fact: 
(a) the authorised recipient in this case, Mr Yat Tan, was a registered migration agent (although there is no requirement in the Act that an 'authorised recipient' must be a registered migration agent);

(b) his Honour was not satisfied that Mr Yat Tan 'did not take responsibility under the Migration Act and within the firm of Tan &amp; Tan for [the appellant's] migration work' [27] and [56];

(c) nor was his Honour satisfied that Mr Yat Tan was 'in any way derelict in his responsibilities as a registered migration agent under the relevant provisions of the Migration Act , in particular s.280(1) ' [28]; or that he was deficient in his 'supervision and responsibility' [29].
